@kghosesbg this statement is part an expression detecting function. It traverses the schema and a cwl object to find nodes that are expressions and returns them. For a part of the schema which consists of a union type, this function uses the validate_js function to find out which part of the schema to choose.

The original design of this function is therefore not to set the "strict" property of validate_js as this would make get_expressions fail for cwl where non strict validation is required or where an array is the input, as an upstream function mutates cwl with an array type to be non conformant to strict interpretation of the cwl specification. I think @michael-kotliar 
@kghosesbg this statement is part an expression detecting function. It traverses the schema and a cwl object to find nodes that are expressions and returns them. For a part of the schema which consists of a union type, this function uses the validate_js function to find out which part of the schema to choose.

The original design of this function is therefore not to set the "strict" property of validate_js as this would make get_expressions fail for cwl where non strict validation is required or where an array is the input, as an upstream function mutates cwl with an array type to be non conformant to strict interpretation of the cwl specification. I think @mr-c changed which (presumably by mistake) to use strict validation while updating the mypy version, breaking this in situations I have described above. Reverting this to previous behaviour shouldn't make this less strict, as proper validation of cwl is done in a separate place

